edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "Today, HTTPS is considered the standard for all websites, not only banking or shopping sites. Modern browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox warn users when they visit HTTP websites, labeling them as \"Not Secure.\" Search engines also favor HTTPS websites in search rankings, encouraging companies to make the switch." --write-media audio/1b372a6d23a52d8cad6425e367775391.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "C# was introduced several years later, in 2000, by Microsoft as part of the .NET initiative. The language was designed to be modern, object-oriented, and suitable for large software systems. Its creators wanted a language that combined productivity, reliability, and strong type checking while benefiting from the growing capabilities of managed runtime environments. Although both languages emerged during the rapid expansion of the Internet era, they were built with different execution models in mind, leading to important distinctions in how programs are processed and executed." --write-media audio/77787765d2513ee6e5824c847d073f40.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "The Journey from Source Code to Execution When a programmer writes code, the computer cannot understand it directly. The source code must first be translated into machine instructions. There are traditionally two approaches to this translation process:" --write-media audio/0e737feb32da3d2b3f8b1088a0f96833.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "Compilation In a compiled language, the source code is translated into another form before the program is executed. The process typically follows these stages: 1. Writing the source code. 2. Running a compiler. 3. Generating executable code. 4. Executing the resulting program. The compiler performs extensive analysis of the code before execution begins. It checks syntax, validates data types, identifies many programming errors, and generates optimized output. Because much of the analysis occurs before the program runs, compiled programs often achieve high performance and reliability." --write-media audio/b814ac4a6aa756eadca5eb1f6084a92e.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "Interpretation An interpreted language follows a different model. Instead of translating the entire program beforehand, an interpreter reads the source code and executes instructions during runtime. The process usually looks like this: 1. Writing the source code. 2. Launching the interpreter. 3. Reading and executing instructions. This approach provides flexibility because changes can be tested immediately without a separate compilation step. However, because translation occurs during execution, interpreted programs have traditionally been slower than compiled programs." --write-media audio/a9d6047e2509cb15e97ea93c9fc43954.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "C# and the Compilation Process C# is often described as a compiled language, but its compilation process is more sophisticated than the traditional model used by older languages. When a C# program is compiled, the compiler does not immediately generate machine code. Instead, it produces an intermediate representation called Intermediate Language (IL). This creates a two-stage execution process:" --write-media audio/468607a25100b2bfd9c7e6028d1e75f5.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "Stage 1: Compilation The C# compiler analyzes the source code and converts it into IL. During this stage, many potential errors are detected, including: Syntax mistakes, Type mismatches, Invalid references, Structural problems within the code. The result is a portable assembly rather than a platform-specific executable." --write-media audio/e6952d11c2c581abf3394324c77c7a94.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "Stage 2: Just-In-Time Compilation When the program starts running, the .NET runtime uses a Just-In-Time (JIT) compiler to translate the IL into native machine code. This means that C# code experiences both compilation and runtime optimization. The JIT compiler can analyze the current hardware environment and generate machine instructions optimized for that specific system. As a result, C# combines many advantages of traditional compilation with the flexibility of a managed runtime environment." --write-media audio/b66640deaf8ec8c1535442046d3e722a.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "JavaScript and Interpretation JavaScript historically followed a pure interpretation model. Early web browsers would read JavaScript source code line by line and execute instructions as they appeared. This allowed developers to modify code and immediately see the results without any compilation step. For many years, this behavior defined JavaScript as a classic interpreted language." --write-media audio/1679ad39aa8e0bff9bbda0cbb2c3f934.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "However, modern JavaScript engines have become significantly more advanced. Today's browsers use sophisticated execution engines that often include: Parsing, Optimization, Bytecode generation, Just-In-Time compilation. Rather than interpreting every instruction repeatedly, modern engines analyze frequently executed sections of code and compile them into optimized machine code. This process dramatically improves performance. As a result, modern JavaScript is no longer purely interpreted. It uses a hybrid execution model that combines interpretation with dynamic compilation techniques." --write-media audio/1bca4e427b4247f21a1d84d3573d2d32.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "Advantages of Early Error Detection One significant difference between C# and JavaScript has traditionally been the stage at which errors are discovered. Because C# performs extensive compilation before execution, many problems are detected before the application runs. For example, assigning a text value to a variable intended for numerical data will typically generate a compilation error." --write-media audio/8168caada8eeaf4604632849e969d5c0.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "In contrast, JavaScript historically delayed many checks until runtime. Some errors would only appear when a specific section of code was executed. This distinction influenced how developers approached testing and debugging. Compilation acted as an additional verification stage, helping programmers identify mistakes earlier in the development process. Although modern JavaScript development tools provide improved static analysis, the language still maintains a more dynamic nature than C#." --write-media audio/a007ab694eae2cc1766551d39d1a9df2.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "Performance Considerations Compilation has long been associated with higher performance. Because compiled code is translated before execution, the processor can execute instructions more directly. Interpreted code, on the other hand, traditionally required continuous translation while running, introducing additional overhead." --write-media audio/dfbc3eb02cb044c4ed20d9f9e0a5566c.mp3
edge-tts --voice en-US-JennyNeural --text "Modern runtime environments have reduced this gap considerably. Just-In-Time compilation allows both C# and JavaScript to benefit from runtime optimization. Nevertheless, C# generally performs more extensive analysis before execution begins, while JavaScript engines often make optimization decisions dynamically as the program runs. This illustrates how the traditional distinction between compiled and interpreted languages has become increasingly blurred." --write-media audio/6922d5f49cfd051cf23c223c7282ff7f.mp3